From far away I saw my new baby girl, squalling and red and not five minutes old, and wondered, dreamily, whose baby it was. lead_paragraph: One day last November, at a stoplight on Route 34 in Derby, Conn., I noticed a truck idling in front of me. It was stout and white, with the requisite grime, and by outward appearance it could have been carrying anything: Portuguese rolls, hanging file folders or maybe replacement gas caps. But when the bumper sticker (Am I driving safely?) referred me to a government website, I became certain the truck was hauling human beings.

abstract: I suspected my wife wasn’t going to join me and my son for Halloween because, once again, she was going psychotic.
snippet: I suspected my wife wasn’t going to join me and my son for Halloween because, once again, she was going psychotic.
lead_paragraph: For my son Jonas’s first Halloween, when he was 5 months old, I dressed the two of us as matching lumberjacks. For the second, we were characters from the movie “Up.” I was Carl, the old man, my wife was Ellie, and Jonas was Russell, the enthusiastic Wilderness Explorer. We tied a dozen balloons to our bulldog’s collar, to make him the house. In our version, the wife didn’t die at the beginning of the movie, and we all lived happily ever after.
